    "created_at": "2015-04-09T18:10:12Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-04-09T18:10:12Z",
    "body": "I agree that there is a certain chance of collisions, but...\n\na) I believe there is a higher chance of accidentally overriding application-specific shortcuts with a global shortcut like `ctrl+alt+b` than with a windows-key-shortcut (even the [global-shortcut documentation](https://github.com/atom/atom-shell/blob/master/docs/api/global-shortcut.md) overrides `ctrl+x` globally in its example...)\n\nb) I don't believe atom-shell should enforce its beliefs about what good shortcut-combinations are and what not upon the developers and users (especially if users can choose shortcuts themselves - they should not be restricted in the way they want to customize their applications and can make their own informed decisions). This is even more true in terms of point a).\n\nc) Not sure, but I believe reserved windows-key-shortcuts can not be easily overwritten anyway, but have to be disabled first in the [registry](http://windowssecrets.com/forums/showthread.php/153042-Disable-some-hotkeys-in-Win-7-Home-Premium).\n"
  },
