    "created_at": "2015-04-19T16:40:17Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-04-19T16:40:17Z",
    "body": "@zcbenz: Not wanting to install keyboard hooks is absolutely reasonable and I'd also argue against that. My intention was not to be able to override existing `win` shortcuts, but to be able to use the ones that are free (which including shortcuts with multiple modifiers are still a lot). \n\nConsidering shortcut collisions between applications may exist with and without the `win` key, I don't think the `win` key should be treated any different than `ctrl` or `alt`. Trying to register a global shortcut that already exists in the system should always throw an exception anyway (again: no matter whether `win` or not).\n\nIndependent of the state on Windows, Linux users should be able to use a meta key like the `win` key. \n\nHaving said all that, implementing the behaviour seems complicated at the moment anyway, as Chromium's [accelerators](https://code.google.com/p/chromium/codesearch#chromium/src/ui/base/accelerators/accelerator.h&sq=package:chromium&type=cs&rcl=1429443319&l=27) don't provide `win` key support and the `win` modifier is also not passed to Windows' [RegisterHotKey](https://msdn.microsoft.com/de-de/library/windows/desktop/ms646309%28v=vs.85%29.aspx) function from the [GlobalShortcutListener](https://code.google.com/p/chromium/codesearch#chromium/src/chrome/browser/extensions/global_shortcut_listener_win.cc&sq=package:chromium&type=cs&q=RegisterAcceleratorImpl&l=67)... Thus I guess Chromium would need to be updated first...\n"
  },
